Part(c)

FIFO (First in First out)- Evicts the page with the longest residency so the first in is the first to be pushed out. This could be in effective as a page that is used frequently will be treated without preferencial bias and when it is accessed again after being evicted it will cause strain on the computer.


LRU (Least Recently Used)-  Each entry is given a timestamp. The oldest timestamp is evicted. If you dont use it a lot it wont place as high a priority. Tracking entrys is costly for the hardware and temporal locality scenario is favored.


LFU (Least Frequently Used)- Frequently used pages are less likely to get evicted. Its uses an incremented counter where everytime its accessed the count goes up. More frequently accessed page get a favorable bias which is good for the hotspot scenario. Unfortunately usage can change over time if someone is playing a game and they love it and play it all the time then they stop because it WAS frequently accessed it will continue to recieve favorable bias despite not being accessed as much anymore.

